pr_review_comment_body:
Because previously, we had things like `templatetags`, which were used in processes. This looked quite hacky to me. Now, filters for use in process definition expressions are defined using separate modules:
```python
FLOW_EXPRESSION_ENGINES = [
    {
        'ENGINE': 'resolwe.flow.expression_engines.jinja',
        'CUSTOM_FILTERS': [
            'resolwe_bio.expression_filters.sample',
        ]
    },
]
```

This line will fail with scalar inputs (I personally like using scalars when doing some exploratory work). My recommendation is to replace this loop with:

```python
mask = sky_diffuse == 0
if isinstance(sky_diffuse, pd.Series):
    diffuse_components = pd.DataFrame(diffuse_components)
    diffuse_components.ix[mask] = 0
else:
    diffuse_components = {k: np.where(mask, 0, v) for k, v in diffuse_components.items()}
```

This has the unfortunate side effect of promoting a scalar to an array, but at least it's consistent with the rest of the api.

It is six. Sorry. And six because we duplicated the legacy datalab lib. Functionally it is 3 (that's why I had 3).

I agree that It is a trade-off between being self-contained and code reusability. I don't feel strongly that the following as an independent code unit:

<script src="/static/components/requirejs/require.js"></script>
<script>
     requirejs.config({
              paths: {
                base: '/static/base',
              },
            });
</script>

It does not save much source code, because these output has a "require.config" section anyway. If we ever want to change anything from the above, chances are that we may need to change the paths in each output cell that require RequireJS anyway.
